<section class="section" aria-labelledby="story-heading">
  <div class="container prose">
    <h2 id="story-heading" class="kicker" style="font-family: var(--font-body)">Matt's story</h2>
    {# Migrated from the original site's "Our Story" and tightened. Matt reviews this page at content sign-off (launch gate 6). #}
    <p class="lead">From when I could walk, I cannot remember a time when gardening was not part of my life.</p>
    <p>It started with helping plant flowers and keep the beds. It became a lifelong study of why some soil grows food effortlessly and some barely grows weeds — a question that led me from gardening into soil biology, and from soil biology into regenerative agriculture.</p>
    <p>The answer, almost always, is the life in the soil. Bacteria, fungi and the larger food web they feed decide whether nutrients reach roots, whether water is held or lost, and whether a garden gets easier or harder every year. When we work with that biology — composting, cover cropping, indigenous microorganisms, fermentation — dead dirt becomes living soil again.</p>
    <p>The stakes are bigger than any one garden. The UN projects close to 9.7 billion people to feed by 2050, and healthy soil is where that food security starts: it protects fresh water, supports biodiversity, and holds carbon instead of releasing it. Coastal Soil Solutions exists to put that understanding to work in the Lower Mainland — and to teach it, so communities can grow more of their own food, well.</p>
    <p>In 2025 we put down our own roots: a working farm where the methods we recommend are the methods we use.</p>
